ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[Because a number of things are capable of causing methemoglobinemia,
including high levels of nitrate/nitrogen in the water, the water sources in
the area should be included in the investigation.
Other environmental agents capable of producing methemoglobinemia include:
aniline dyes, aromatic amines, arsine, butyl nitrites, chlorates,
chlorobenzene, chromates, combustion products, dimethyltoluidine, foods
containing nitrates or nitrites (including well water), isobutyl nitrite,
naphthalene, nitroaniline, nitrobenzene, nitrofurans, nitrophenol,
nitrosobenzene, resorcinol, silver nitrate, and trinitrotoluene.
A number of pharmaceutical agents may also produce clinical signs, including
local anesthetic agents (e.g. benzocaine, lidocaine, prilocaine), amyl
nitrite, chloroquine, dapsone, nitrates, nitrites, nitroglycerin,
nitroprusside, phenacetin, phenazopyridine, primaquine, quinones, and
sulfonamides.
This could be an extensive investigation. We look forward to an
authoritative account of the findings. - Mod.TG]
...................tg/pg/jw


